<subsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title> Initial Conditions </title>
	
	<p>
        Solving a differential equation typically begins with finding its general solution. This provides a template, containing constants, that shows the form of all possible solutions. For example, here is an equation with its general solution 
        <men xml:id="initial-condition-gen-soln">
			y'' - y' - 12y = 0 \qquad \os{\text{general}}{\us{\text{solution}}{\longrightarrow}} \qquad y(t) = c_1e^{-3t} + c_2e^{4t}
		</men>
        where <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m> are constants that can take any value, representing infinitely many possible solutions.
    </p>

    <p>
        In practical applications, we often need a unique solution that fits specific criteria. These criteria are provided as <term>initial conditions</term>, which are known values of the solution or its derivatives at a specific point. Initial conditions allow us to determine values for the constants in the general solution yielding a particular solution corresponding to these conditions. When a differential equation is accompanied by initial conditions, it is called an <term>initial value problem</term>.
    </p>

	<p>
        For instance, consider the free fall of an object due to gravity, where <m>s(t)</m> is the position (distance from the ground) of the object at time <m>t</m>. The motion is described by the differential equation:
        <me>
            \os{\text{acceleration}}{\scriptsize\text{of position}} 
			\ \rightarrow \quad s''(t) = -32 \text{ ft/s}^2 \quad \leftarrow \ 
			\os{\text{gravity}}{\scriptsize\text{constant}} 
        </me>
        The general solution is:
        <me>
            s(t) = c_1 + c_2t - 16t^2.
        </me>
        To find a unique solution, we need additional information about the problem. Suppose we know:
    </p>

	<tabular>
        <col right="minor" halign="center" />
        <col halign="center" />
        <row bottom="minor">
            <cell>Information at <m>t=0</m></cell>
            <cell>Initial Condition</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell>The object is initially at the top of a 100 ft building.</cell>
            <cell><m>s(0) = 100 \text{ ft}</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell>The object is dropped from rest (initial velocity is zero).</cell>
            <cell><m>s'(0) = 0 \text{ ft/s}</m></cell>
        </row>
    </tabular>

    <p>
        Substituting these initial conditions into the general solution allows us to solve for <m>c_1</m> and <m>c_2</m>. Here's the process:
    </p>

    <tabular>
        <col right="minor" halign="center" />
        <col right="minor" halign="center" />
        <col halign="left" />
        <row bottom="minor">
            <cell>Initial Condition</cell>
            <cell>Applied to</cell>
            <cell>Gives</cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell><m>s(0) = 100 \text{ ft}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>s(t) = c_1 + c_2t - 16t^2</m></cell>
            <cell><m>100 = c_1 + c_2(0) - 16(0)^2</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell><m>100 = c_1</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell><m>s'(0) = 0 \text{ ft/s}</m></cell>
            <cell><m>s'(t) = c_2 - 32t</m></cell>
            <cell><m>0 = c_2 - 32(0)</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell><m>c_2 = 0</m></cell>
        </row>
    </tabular>

	 <p>
        With <m>c_1 = 100</m> and <m>c_2 = 0</m>, the unique solution for this problem is:
        <me>
            s(t) = 100 - 16t^2.
        </me>
    </p>

    <p>
        Let's practice applying initial conditions to find particular solutions.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="p1-c2-s5-example-10">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the initial value problem:
                <me xml:id="p1-c2-s5-example-1-de0"> 
					\frac{dy}{dx} = 2xy - 6x, \quad y(0) = 2.
				</me>
                The general solution is:
                <me>
                    y = ce^{x^2} + 3.
                </me>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The initial condition <m>y(0) = 2</m> tells us that <m>y</m> must equal 2 when <m>x = 0</m>. Substituting into the general solution:
                <md>
					<mrow> y =  ce^{x^2} + 3 \quad \overset{y\ =\ 2,\ x\ =\ 0}{\Rightarrow} \quad	2	=\amp\  ce^{0^2} + 3	</mrow>
					<mrow>							 												2	=\amp\  c + 3		</mrow>
					<mrow>																			-1	=\amp\  c			</mrow>
				</md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Thus, the particular solution is:
                <me>
                    y = -e^{x^2} + 3.
                </me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
        Visualizing solutions with initial conditions can further enhance understanding. For instance, <xref ref="initial-conditions-figure-1" /> shows the initial condition <m>y(0) = 2</m> as the point <m>(0, 2)</m> on the <m>y</m>-axis. The blue curve represents the unique particular solution passing through this point.
    </p>
	
	<sidebyside widths="46% 2% 50%" margins="0%">

		<stack>
			<p>
				<em>In the graph, the point on the <m>y</m>-axis is the initial condition. You can change the initial condition by dragging the point up and down along the <m>y</m>-axis.</em>
			</p>

			<p>
				As you drag the point, make the following observations:
			</p>

			<ul marker="square">
				<li>
					<p>
						Each new value of <m>y(0)</m> determines a new value for <m>c</m>, resulting in a different particular solution (blue curve).
					</p>
				</li>
                <li>
					<p>
						Only one particular solution from the family (green curves) passes through any given initial condition.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ul>
		</stack>

		<p/>

		<figure xml:id="initial-conditions-figure-1">
